<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GATHERING MISTLETOE FOR EXTRA SMACKERS
FOR ONE TEXAS TOWN, A TRADITION MEANS MONEY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Around here, it's everywhere, growing wild and fast and furious in fat
little clumps, hanging from bare branches of the mesquite, elm and water oaks
like ornaments on a Christmas tree.;   "We have gone out and collected
mistletoe for years and years and years," Seider said. "My parents did it. My
mother-in-law did it. My wife does it.";   And now his son, Ashley, 14, is out
climbing trees on weekends trying to yank down the mistletoe.;   Mistletoe --
an evergreen with thick leaves and clusters of tiny white berries -- has long
had its lure. Ancient priests once handed out sprigs as good-luck charms, and
people hung it over their doors to ward off evil.;   In Scandinavian
mythology, mistletoe was associated with the goddess of love. Some think that
is the root of the romantic Christmas custom: kissing under the mistletoe.;  
Tradition has it that a person caught standing under the mistletoe must
forfeit a kiss. The kisses must equal the number of white berries.;   Nobody
around here pays much mind to that tradition -- probably because it's so
difficult not to stand under mistletoe.;   Today, much of the fresh mistletoe
bought and sold at Christmas comes out of trees within 100 miles of Priddy,
population 75. (They're sure about that number because somebody drove up the
street once and counted everybody.);   In a red-brick warehouse along Priddy's
main street, the smell of mistletoe is in the air. Leftovers are on the floor
of Tiemann's Holiday Mistletoe Co. Trash bins are filling with mistletoe that
didn't quite make the grade. (Not green enough or too few white berries.);  
People of old may have thought mistletoe was magical because the plant grows
high up in the tree without touching the ground, fueling beliefs that
mistletoe was "heaven-sent.";   Texans, however, know better.;   The mistletoe
is in the tree because it is eating dinner there.;   "It is a parasite. It has
roots that grow down into the wood and they actually feed on the tree. If it
gets bad enough, it will kill the tree," said Jerral Johnson, a plant
pathologist at Texas A&amp;M University. "We get a lot of calls from people who
want to get rid of it.";   But that's hard to do. Scientists have yet to
develop herbicides that kill mistletoe without killing the tree. So once it
takes root in the tree, like an unwelcome holiday guest, it's hard to get rid
of.;   "I don't care much for mistletoe myself," Seider said. "But it sure
comes in handy at Christmastime."; Facts and myth; (box) Semiparasitic
evergreen plant -- North American variety is Phoradendron serotinum -- that
attaches itself to trees, then taps through bark to draw out nutrients.; (box)
Berries are poisonous to humans and most animals but not birds.; (box) In
North America, it is found mainly on deciduous trees.; (box) State flower of
Oklahoma.; (box) In Norse mythology, mistletoe killed Balder, the god of
beauty, goodness and light. All living things had sworn an oath not to harm
him, and because of that, the gods would throw things at Balder with seeming
impunity. But the god Loki, who was jealous of Balder, found out that
mistletoe alone hadn't sworn the oath. Loki made a mistletoe dart and guided
the blind god Hoder's hand as he threw it. The dart killed Balder instantly.;
