<HEADLINE>  KISS-UNDER-MISTLETOE POLL SMACKS OF COMMERCIALISM  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recchi is a columnist for the Fort Lauderdale, Fla., News &amp; Sun-Sentinel.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     So I would not have been a very good candidate for the "mistletoe poll" I
read about early this week.;   For those who haven't seen it, the poll asked
1,005 people to choose from a list of celebrities the one they would most like
to meet under the mistletoe.;   Within a minuscule margin of error, the
results were predictable.;   Women chose Mel Gibson, Paul Newman, Kevin
Costner, Harrison Ford, Arnold Schwarzenegger, Norman Schwarzkopf, Michael
Jordan and Warren Beatty.;   Men picked Paula Abdul as their first choice,
followed by Julia Roberts, Michelle Pfeiffer, Candice Bergen, Madonna, Demi
Moore, Whitney Houston and Annette Bening.;   Of course, you are skeptical of
my assertion that I would not be interested in kissing any of those people. I
suspect even my wife would not believe it.;   But it's true. Kissing someone I
don't know has about as much appeal to me as planting a smack on a hunk of raw
beef.;   So to me, the question is not why wouldn't I, but why would I want to
engage in casual osculation with a stranger? Why would anyone?;   No, I take
that back. I understand why anyone would. Like I said, there was a time when I
did. There were games of spin the bottle and post office when I was a kid.
There were also games of pony express (which is just like post office only
with more horsing around).;   Kissing females I barely knew was fun in those
days. But then, so was making crude noises with my armpit when the math
teacher had his back turned.;   In all modesty, I believe I've matured quite a
bit since those days. Having married an excellent kisser nearly 20 years ago,
the thought of kissing a stranger seems silly.;   Press my lips against
Madonna's? With all due respect, I'll pass. And for the same reason Grandma
Recchi once gave me for not putting coins in my mouth: "You don't know where
they've been.";   Besides, would it mean something? Nope. Would it change my
life? Perhaps, but only for the worse -- particularly if someone in my family
found out.;   In all fairness, however, those questioned in the mistletoe poll
probably didn't give it that much thought.;   We see so many of those
frivolous polls that most people don't bother to question them. As a
columnist, however, it is part of my duty to do exactly that.;   This one, for
example, was conducted by Bruskin Associates for a major credit card company.
Why, you wonder, is a credit card company interested in knowing who has the
most tempting kisser?;   It's not. But the people who run that company know
that there is a public fascination with such polls. They pop up throughout the
year, telling us which celebrity has the squarest jaw, the best derriere,
sexiest eyes, best wardrobe and worst wardrobe.;   The results make perfect
fillers for TV and radio news, as well as for newspaper "people" columns.;  
In this case, it fulfills two purposes for the credit card company.;   The
most subtle of these is the mention of mistletoe, reminding us that Christmas
is only two months away, so maybe we should unholster that credit card and
start shopping. Sure enough, one of the other "revelations" in the poll was
that two-thirds of us don't start Christmas shopping until November.;   The
other, more obvious benefit to the credit card company is that its name is
mentioned free in many newspapers and on TV and radio.;   That I have
neglected to mention it here can be attributed only to pure spite.;   Maybe
I'm not as mature as I thought.  </TEXT>
