<DATELINE>BIG CYPRESS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When poor pupils at a small school on an
Indian reservation wrote Santa Claus asking for pencils and
notebooks, touched postal workers responded by buying the children
more than 150 gifts.
   ``They weren't asking for things like computers and Nintendo
games,'' said Twila Fairtrace, secretary to the West Palm Beach
postmaster. ``These letters were different because they were asking
for the basics. Most of them asked for school supplies.''
   Fairtrace, who during the Christmas season reviews letters to
Santa, told co-workers about the 21 letters from Ahfachkee School on
the Big Cypress Indian Reservation. About 60 workers then raised
money for gifts for the school's 48 pupils.
   Gift-wrapped presents delivered to the children Friday included
pencils, pens, notebooks and reams of paper, as well as clothing and
toys.
   ``What really got to me,'' postal worker Dawn Haugen said, ``was
when one little girl was telling some others, `Look what I got! I've
got pencils and paper and crayons and glue and everything!'''
   When a kindergartener hugged post office ``elf'' Joann
Goodbridge, the woman was so overcome with emotion she ran behind a
van used to deliver the gifts.
   ``When that little girl threw her arms around me, I just lost
it,'' Goodbridge said. ``I couldn't help crying.''
   Tom Bernos, assistant principal at the south-central Florida
school, said the little girl has 15 brothers and sisters.
   Postal workers said the project boosted morale.
   ``I walked into work, and everybody's there early, on their own
time, wrapping presents,'' said employee John Nasipak. ``We're
thinking about seeing if we can't make this an annual project, using
different schools in needy neighborhoods.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MISTLETOE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During the month of December, Mistletoe
Postmaster A.B. Couch said he handles twice as much mail as he does
all the rest of the year.
   ``They send it here to get the `Mistletoe' postmark on it,''
Couch said. ``I don't count the mail, but I suppose about 500 pieces
came in this morning.''
   The mail arrives by the only route to the tiny post office _ a
twisting, six-mile gravel road.
   ``The story goes that the post office got its name because trees
on the surrounding hills were full of mistletoe,'' said Couch, the
postmaster since 1969. ``That bad winter of 1977 about wiped it out,
though.''
   There isn't much in Mistletoe besides an abandoned Presbyterian
church, some barns and Couch's wood-frame house.
   Inside the house, the kitchen is to the right, the U.S. Post
Office to the left.
   Until December, Couch and his assistant postmaster _ his wife of
22 years, Judy _ process about 2,300 pieces of mail for the 16
customers tucked among the Owsley County hills.
   But in December, mail from all over the country and several
foreign nations arrives at the post office, addressed to him.
Inside, Couch finds addressed, stamped envelopes, onto which he
stamps the coveted postmark and then mails the finished products
back out.
   Couch said he doesn't keep track of who sends what, so he's not
sure whether he has customers who mail to Mistletoe year after year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MAMMOTH CAVE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 50-foot vaulted ceilings of a
section of Mammoth Cave helped Christmas carolers create an unusual
sound.
   ``You would think when you go down in a cave you'd get echoes,
but you don't,'' said Ron Wagner, musical director of the Mammoth
Cave Cavemen Barbershop Chorus. ``It's almost perfect down there.''
   The cave's acoustics, which in years past have attracted opera
stars, violinists and Shakespearean actors, surrounded the carolers
with a rich, resonant sound.
   ``It was very moving. It's kind of religious down here in the
cave,'' said Carolyn McNeill of Bowling Green.
   About 800 people, mainly residents from western Kentucky counties
surrounding Mammoth Cave National Park, attended the carroling
session Friday night 150 feet below the earth's surface.
   The event was inspired by an 1883 Christmas party thrown by
guests at the Mammoth Cave Hotel, said Mark Willis, special-events
coordinator for the park. That group decorated a cave room with a
cedar tree covered with ribbons, strung popcorn and sang carols by
the light of whale-oil lamps.
   The performers, including church choirs and area singing clubs,
took their turns on a natural stage of cave rubble.
   The performance, which lasted more than an hour, ended when the
singers led the crowd out of the cave in a candlelight procession.
   As they headed to the surface for cookies, hot chocolate and
apple cider, the group sang ``Silent Night.''
