<LEADPARA>  IN THE next few weeks, millions of Americans will buy plants associated with
the holidays: poinsettias, mistletoe and holly, to name a few.;   A word of
advice. Display them cautiously. Your child or pet could become ill or die
from eating some of these plants.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  KEEP HOLIDAY PLANTS AWAY FROM KIDS, PETS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Holiday  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     People have been under the impression that eating a poinsettia can cause
death. Not so, says the Society of American Florists. The only reported death
from someone's eating a poinsettia came about the turn of the century, and
that was not confirmed.;   But eating a poinsettia probably will cause nausea
and even vomiting, according to poison-control centers.;   There's an obvious
answer. Keep the plants out of the reach of children and pets.;   (check)
MISTLETOE -- A wonderful plant. I love the excuse it gives to smooch.;   But
eating this plant is a definite mistake. Diarrhea and vomiting almost always
result, and a few deaths have been reported.;   Again, keep it out of the
reach of children and away from pets. Because mistletoe is usually hung, make
