<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this seaside community
can kiss holiday mistletoe goodbye, along with Christmas trees and
sleigh bells, because the city has given traditional street
decorations the heave ho-ho-ho.
   Rudolph has been replaced by Flipper. Jonathon Livingston
Seagull outranks the snowman.
   Old St. Nick will ride into town under a wave of ocean-themed
vinyl banners depicting sea gulls, dolphins and kelp.
   ``The generic candle and Christmas wrapping could go in Des
Moines or Cincinnati,'' said artist Laddie John Dill.
   ``I wanted something that was more tailored to Santa Monica ...
which has become the arts center of California,'' added Dill, who
designed the banners with graphic artist John Van Hamersveld.
   The Santa Monica Area Chamber of Commerce commissioned the 225
banners, which are being strung up on lampposts this week. Each
3-foot-by-7-foot banner shows a gull, dolphin or sea weed.
   ``We didn't want to just make it Christmas bells and carolers,''
said Michael Segal, who headed the design project as a member of
the chamber's central business district advisory group.
   ``The kelp gives a mistletoe feeling, the dolphins are in a
wreath design and the gull looks like a Christmas dove of peace,''
Segal said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Ohio River city's version of
Hollywood's sidewalk of stars honoring entertainment greats will
star anyone who wants to pay $40.
   For that fee, city officials will engrave the donor's name in a
brick that will be part of a new sidewalk at the city's Harris
Riverfront Park.
   Proceeds from the sale will go toward improvements at the park,
Mayor Bobby Nelson said.
   The city's Urban Renewal Authority plans to install 1,548
engraved bricks and will flank them with 3,846 pieces of plain
masonry.
   ``We're not tearing anything up. We're just adding to it,'' said
Ed Diehl, city urban renewal director.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cody Jacobs is giving thanks for a year
that's been his dream come true as one of former President Ronald
Reagan's biggest fans.
   Jacobs' good fortune started last summer when he was named one
of five Reagan Scholars and awarded four years free tuition at
Reagan's alma mater, tiny Eureka College.
   Then, the 19-year-old Arkansas City, Kan., native was elected
freshman class president, putting him right on his self-imposed
schedule for reaching his ultimate life's goal: president of the
United States.
   Next week, Jacobs is going to California to meet his idol and
role model.
   ``This will fullfill my lifelong dream,'' Jacobs said from his
dorm room, where the walls are covered with pictures of the Gipper,
framed letters from the former commander-in-chief and campaign
posters.
   ``I'm a total Reagan fanatic,'' Jacobs said. ``It started in
fourth grade when a teacher sparked my awareness in politics with a
real intense history lesson on the presidency.''
   School officials say Jacobs' devotion to Reagan is genuine.
   ``Cody is unique and may be the most politically inclined of the
Reagan Scholars we've had since the program started in 1983,'' said
Rolf Craft, director of the scholarship program.
