<HEAD>Holiday Decorations, Use Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual crop of holiday greenery is
sprouting in American homes. Enjoying those decorations also means
using some care to avoid fire and keep children from poisoning
themselves accidentally.
   Some of the most popular plants used for holiday decorations are
poisonous, according to the National Clearinghouse for Poison
Control Centers.
   Holly is popular because of its bright green leaves and red
berries, but the berries can be dangerous if eaten.
   Swallowing the berries can lead to diarrhea, vomiting and
depression of the central nervous system, the Poison Control Center
says.
   Mistletoe berries are another danger, containing chemicals that
can cause abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, high blood pressure
and even collapse of the circulatory system, medical authorities
say. In addition, diarrhea, weakness, low blood pressure and other
problems can occur from eating any part of the yew plant.
   Those lovely red poinsettias can be troublesome too. Health
officials say that if any part of the plant is swallowed it can
cause abdominal discomfort, while the milky sap from the leaves can
cause an irritation or dermatitis in some people.
   Another decoration danger is fire, with Christmas trees and other
greenery a major problem.
   Try to keep the tree as moist as possible, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission urges. After bringing it home cut off a few inches
of the base and place it in water. And keep the tree well watered
when in use.
   Buyers should avoid dry trees, of course. A good test is to pull
on some needles and see if they resist. The harder they are to pull
off, the better.
   If the cut part of the tree is sticky with resin, that's a good
sign.
   Try bouncing the tree on the ground a bit: a shower of falling
needles tells you that it's too dry.
   When going to bed or leaving the house turn off lights on trees
and other decorations, the commission said. And never use candles on
trees or near greens.
   Check all lights for broken bulbs and frayed wires before
installing them, and discard any damaged strings.
   Never use lights on a metallic artificial tree. A faulty string
can cause the entire tree to become charged, potentially causing an
electrocution. This type of tree can be brightened by a spotlight
shining on it.
   Other safety suggestions from the Safety Commission include:
   _Artificial snow sprays can irritate the lungs if inhaled. Read
the directions carefully and follow them.
   _Wear gloves when decorating with spun glass ``angel hair'' to
avoid irritation to eyes and skin.
   _Use plastic ``tinsel'' rather than the leaded kinds which could
be hazardous if ingested.
   _In homes with children be especially careful of using fragile
decorations or items with sharp points or which resemble candy or
food.
   _Before lighting any fire make sure trimmings and wrapping paper
are clear of the area. Do not burn wrappings in the fireplace.
</TEXT>
