<LP>
   The Halloween candy has barely been eaten, and the
Thanksgiving turkey won't be dressed for weeks. But already,
it's beginning to look a lot like Christmas.
   Turn on the tube at random, and you'll see holly and
mistletoe, or expensive toys wrapped up in bows. Hasbro
Inc.'s Playskool toy line kicked off its holiday campaign
last night on NBC's "L.A. Law." Lionel Corp.'s Kiddie City
toy-store chain started its Christmas advertising on
television last month. And Tott's champagne is already
ringing in the holidays for E.&amp;J. Gallo Winery.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "In this kind of environment, a lot of advertisers are
trying to get a jump start," says Dan Owen, president of
Playskool, Pawtucket, R.I.
   Once upon a time not very long ago, the Christmas selling
season began after Thanksgiving. Advertisers didn't dare trot
out the Christmas trees and snow scenes until after Santa
Claus made his first appearance at the annual Macy's
Thanksgiving Day Parade.
   But over the past few years, advertisers have steadily
pushed forward the "holiday season," this year rolling it all
the way up to Halloween. TV viewers last weekend were
bombarded by Christmas messages, and more are on the way
every day. The way things are going, next year's Christmas
season may start just after Labor Day.
   Yet the early advertising assault may well backfire. For
starters, "there's no evidence earlier advertising will
increase {sales} volume at all," notes Larry Light of
Arcature, a Stamford, Conn., marketing consultant.
   The early birds may be able to gain market share at the
expense of competitors, Mr. Light says. But if everybody
advertises early -- and it sure looks as if they are -- then
that advantage is wiped out, too. With advertisers all
rushing in long before Thanksgiving, "then you have increased
marketing costs without increasing share or volume," says Mr.
Light. In other words, everybody loses.
   Most advertisers aren't planning to spend more than last
year, they're just starting earlier. That means they may be
blowing their budgets before people are really ready to buy.
When consumers finally are ready to listen, the ad spending
may already be wiped out. Worse, the Christmas selling season
may peak too early. The already troubled retailing industry
doesn't need yet another season of "after-Christmas"
discounts and sales beginning well before Christmas Eve.
   Advertisers, though, aren't listening. They can't afford
to wait, since so many competitors are starting now. All want
to be on the consumer's mind before he or she even starts
shopping.
   "When it's Christmas time, you don't have to tell anybody
to shop," reasons Alan Pollak, whose Pollak Agency in
Metuchen, N.J., creates ads for Kiddie City. His goal is "to
get people to think of Kiddie City earlier," so it is
top-of-mind when they do go shopping.
   Kiddie City desperately needs to keep sales levels high
because Lionel currently is in Chapter 11 bankruptcy
proceedings. The chain ran its first TV spots in October,
about a month earlier than usual. It began its radio campaign
in September, and ran some test ads as early as August. Most
recently, Kiddie City has been hawking its layaway policy
with the intentionally ungrammatical "If you lay away, you
won't lay awake." Notes Mr. Pollak, "In this economy, that's
important to a lot of people."
   Playskool started its new prime-time campaign about two
weeks earlier than last year. "By starting earlier, it's
going to give us a longer selling season," says Playskool's
Mr. Owen. "In a relatively soft retail environment, I have a
major opportunity to increase market share this year."
   Playskool is combining its early start with more ads in
prime time in an attempt to muscle in on recession-wracked
competitors. Each ad in its new campaign, dubbed the
"Playskool Photo Album," features "snapshots" of family life
and prominently highlights several toys.
   Marketers pushing for a head start are taking their cue
from such advertisers as Time Warner Inc.'s Sports
Illustrated magazine, which typically begins its
Christmas-themed TV ad campaigns in October. Its commercials,
which are direct-response subscription pleas, "seem to do
better the earlier we start," explains Linda Warren, consumer
marketing director. "Others have realized it works. The
stores are starting to catch on," she suggests.
   Indeed, many advertisers are forced to get their messages
out early because the stores themselves have already begun
pushing Christmas merchandise. Boxes of Christmas cards
appeared in September. And with a full 46 days till the
yuletide, department stores are already loading up on the
tinsel and canned carols.
</TEXT>
