   Some people claim to like fruitcake, so maybe there are
even fans who cheer the annual December ritual of lawsuits
challenging public displays of creches and menorahs. Still,
maybe next year the American Civil Liberties Union could just
send out greeting cards to mark the season the way the rest
of us do.
   The ACLU has managed to get the Supreme Court to rule
often enough in cases over the years that by now no one knows
when a holiday display supposedly violates the Establishment
Clause. The justices seem to require some secular quota for
any exhibit of religion. Cities spend the other 11 months
considering whether to show the Three Wise Men riding into
town on plastic reindeer or maybe erect a Frosty the Snowman
to light the menorah.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   This year's lawsuits include one that began before
Christmas 1989. The ACLU challenged the right of Ottawa,
Illinois, to display 16 paintings depicting the life of
Christ in a public park. The lawsuit dragged on so long that
the city and the local Jaycees who organized the exhibit
dropped out of the case, transferring the display to another
group that agreed to defend it in court. San Diego is
considering privatization as a solution to the church-state
problem that a federal court said was created by crosses atop
Mount Soledad and Mount Helix, longtime symbols of the city.
The question in Casper, Wyoming, is whether a creche is
secular enough if there's also a Christmas tree and an
ice-skating display.
   The good news is that even the ACLU has its limits. The
Washington Post reported that an anxious parent asked the
local branch office to sue a school for daring to include
"Christmas, holly and mistletoe" on a spelling test. The
ACLU's Arthur Spitzer told the parent that there was no
constitutional problem here. "We decided not to take any
action," Mr. Spitzer said. "And people say the ACLU has no
judgment." Have a very merry holiday, Mr. Spitzer.
