dangers to the person with Alzheimer's. Put all matches and lighters away after 
using. If you can child-proof your house for the holidays, you can make it safe 
for the person with dementia, Caron-Parker said. 
</P>
<P>
* Use only unbreakable ornaments on the Christmas tree and hang them with 
ribbon, not metal hooks. Remember that such traditional holiday plants as 
poinsetti a, mistletoe and holiday are poisonous if ingested. 
</P>
<P>
* Avoid blinking holiday lights. They seem to increase the confusion and 
agitation of people with dementia. Shiny, reflective wrapping paper that causes 
visual distortions also seems to have this effect and should be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
* Gifts should be kept out of sight until they are exchanged. Left under the 
tree or elsewhere in the open they increase visual clutter. The person with 
Alzheimer's may also open gifts that are left out, whomever they are meant for. 
</P>
<P>
* Limit the number of holiday visitors, prepare them for the changes they will 
see in the affected person and schedule their visits for morning and early 
afternoon when people with dementia are usually at their best. 
</P>
