<HEAD>Christmas Spirit Takes True Grit in Desert Shield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IN EASTERN SAUDI ARABIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every soldier in the U.S. Army's
1st Cavalry Division is getting a gift package for Christmas - even
if it's only a pair of government-issue green socks.
   Services to mark the birth of Jesus and secular yuletide symbols
such as Christmas trees are being hidden behind closed tent flaps
so as not to offend the Moslem hosts of the Desert Shield
deployment.
   Carols are sung in combat boots and Christmas spirit is as hard
to find as reindeer in a camel herd, so troops fight to keep their
minds off the thousands of miles separating them from loved ones.
   ``If I start thinking about it, I get lonely,'' said Army Spec.
Robert Dennett, 29, of Rutherford, Texas, whose three kids will be
opening Christmas gifts without him. ``My wife said she was going
to save a bunch of presents 'til I got back and do Christmas all
over again.''
   Christmas was intentionally subdued in Saudi Arabia, where
strict Islamic codes ban the worship of other religions. That means
songs like ``White Christmas'' are preferred over ``Silent Night''
on the military radio stations.
   The only celebrity to visit is Bob Hope, the war-horse
troubadour who first entertained U.S. combat troops 50 years ago.
   Meals and mail provided some Christmas cheer.
   Military cooks prepared 150,000 pounds of rolled turkey and
4,000 whole turkeys for the 280,000 U.S. service members brought to
Saudi Arabia after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait on Aug. 2. The goal is
to get a hot Christmas dinner to all the troops, even those closest
to the Kuwaiti border.
   The main lifeline to home is the average of 400 tons of mail a
day, hauled in on at least five planeloads.
   Inmates at Szabo Correctional Services at Dublin, Calif., sent
boxes of cookies to officers. Josefina Ceja of Pomona, Calif.,
dispatched homemade tortillas to her son. Another mom sent a
finger-painting set.
   ``Even the camels see the mail trucks coming because the troops
feed them cookies,'' said Major Gen. William ``Gus'' Pagonis, head
of logistics for the largest U.S. military operation since Vietnam.
``Like other creatures of the wild, they learn real fast the GIs
will feed them.''
   So many packages addressed to ``any soldier'' were received that
each of the 20,000 soldiers of the 1st Cavalry Division can expect
to get a Christmas package. Those who don't get a civilian gift can
expect to get military T-shirts, underwear and socks.
   ``It might be a pair of green socks. It might be a Frisbee. But
we've got one gift for every soldier,'' said Maj. Steve Stacey, the
division's personnel officer.
   He also delivered the 1st Cavalry's message to the folks on the
home front: ``Although we're homesick and we miss you, we're with
you in spirit. We can't send any presents, so we send your our
love.''
   Midnight Mass has its own subtleties in the sand. Some services
were to be moved up to dusk. That way, troops wouldn't violate the
military ban on lights in the desert night.
   Lt. Theodore Borger, one of three Roman Catholic priests tending
to the spiritual needs of the 1st Marine Division, was planning
about 20 services.
   He was going to break out his special folding combat altar, but
was not going to deliver any special message.
   ``There will be others that will talk to them about the evil or
war. That's not my job,'' said Borger, 35, of Ottumwa, Iowa.
   Meanwhile, troops entertained themselves by singing lyrics to
their favorite holiday tunes. The Marine version of ``Jingle
Bells'' went like this:
   ``Dashing through the sand, with an M16 in hand, terrorizing the
land, looking for Hussein. Treads on tracks will ring, giving
troops a fright, opens up the door, we get out and fight.''
   A few Marines stuck up stockings in their tents, and Cpl.
Vincent Buck, 21 decorated the radiator grill of his truck with a
plastic holy wreath his mother sent from Santa Barbara, Calif.
   His dad sent mistletoe.
   There were not to be any Christmas spirits of the alcoholic
variety because of Saudi Arabia's strict ban on booze. So Maj. John
Porter of the Army's Battle Command Training Program made other
plans.
   ``We're going to have a party on the beach,'' said Porter, 38,
of Leavenworth, Kan. ``We're going to have near-beer, near-wine,
and the next morning we're going to wake up with near hangovers.''
   Some combat training has been scheduled for Christmas Day, but
most troops will have a light day.
   ``It's just another day in the desert,'' said Pfc. Mark Idleman,
19, of Wilson, Okla., a tank crewman with the 32nd Armored Regiment
of the 1st Cavalry Division.
   ``Christmas is a bad topic over here,'' said Lt. Tyler Randolph,
24, of MacLean, Va., who serves in one of the units of the Army's
18th Airborne Corps. ``It just makes you miss everybody more.''
