<TEXT>
   Donald R. Leal ("Yellowstone Burns as Park Managers Play Politics," editorial page, Aug. 26) described well the dilemma facing park managers trying to "preserve" the living, changing biological entity that a forest is. 
The fires in Yellowstone, which have consumed upward of one-fourth of the park's forests as of this writing, provide a stark lesson in the ecology that has governed nearly all of North America's forests over eons of time. 

   Lightning and, later, primitive man burned them regularly. 
When the first U.S. cavalry unit entered the park in 1870, Lt. Gustavus Doane reported that "the woods were . . . on fire in every direction." 
These fires, he said, were set by Indians hunting wildlife. 
The white man ran the Indians out, of course, thus beginning a transformation of the park. 

   Yellowstone's lodgepole pine forests are today grossly overaged, ranging up to 400 years old. 
Lodgepole becomes an old tree by age 60 to 80 and thereafter easily falls prey to insects and disease. 
The park's forests are now riddled with mountain pine beetles, one of the most destructive pests in western North America. 
In most of the park, more than half the trees are dead or dying. 
Dwarf mistletoe, a parasitic plant, infests the geriatric stands, further weakening them to beetle attacks. 
Fallen trees lie in jackstrawed piles everywhere, a furnace of fuel waiting for the spark that finally came. 
It's a sick old forest. 

   The beetles are also active in federal forests outside the park, but there the U.S. Forest Service has been permitted to salvage the dead trees, removing the wood and saving it for man's use. 
This reduced the intensity of fires there, and logging roads aided firefighters in controlling them more quickly. 
No one advocates logging in the park, but what is happening there demonstrates the fallacy of the "hands-off" philosophy Mr. Leal says environmentalists have forced on park managers. 

   The lesson for us is that, in forests not set aside as parks or wilderness areas, we can prevent such wholesale destruction under management programs that renew the forest by harvesting mature trees, removing the fuel for use in products and generating new growth. 

   What will happen next to Yellowstone's burned-over forests? 
Lodgepole is a tree peculiarly adapted to renewal by fire. 
It produces cones that may remain tightly shut over the life of the tree until opened by the intense heat of fire. 
So the burned areas are well seeded, so much so that they will resprout in even-aged "dog-hair" thickets so dense that neither man nor game animals can penetrate them. 
Park people who are predicting the resurgence of open meadows will find that those openings close up quickly, since at the extreme as many as 175,000 tightly packed lodgepole pines per acre may soon cover the land. 
These dense thickets become grossly stagnated and can persist indefinitely. 

   The short-term effect of the fires will be to stimulate growth of aspen and other herbaceous plants, and this will produce an explosion of wildlife numbers. 
When the lodgepole thickets take over the land, however, a major die-off of wildlife will follow. 

   In the meantime, snags of the old forest will be falling, and new jackstrawed piles of fire-killed trees may result in major fires again some years from now. 
This could help to thin out some of the dog-hair stands and provide more open spacing once again for the surviving trees. 

   And then it will all begin again. 

   Laurence D. Wiseman
   President, American Forest Council
   Washington
   ---
   It is ironic that the ideology of the Wilderness Society's Steven Whitney (letters to the editor, Sept. 12) tells him that a forest managed by a logging company is worse than a burned forest: "Turning over our national parks and forests to the private sector may make sense to a logging company, but not to a sportsman, tourist, scientist, eagle or grizzly." 

   Though no one has found a way of polling animals, I wager that grizzlies and eagles would rather live in a managed forest than die in a burning forest. 
As for sportsmen, tourists and scientists, why wouldn't they rather visit green, managed forests than desolate, charred woodlands? 

   Apparently the "environmental elite" would rather see their cherished forests go up in smoke than allow the private sector to save the environment. 

   Paul Craig Roberts
   Center for Strategic and International Studies
   Washington
